Namaste,


I agree to this idea totally that any or more of the paths can b=
e mixed by an individual. And I agree 200% with the statement that Jyana Yo=
ga needs one to be brutally honesty with our own selves. Which at various t=
imes we are not, because the ego (sense of I-ness) loves to shield our own =
vital flaws from ourselves to provide ever so slightly an illusion of wellb=
eing, progress and knowledge.

However, I slightly disagree with the statem=
ent on RajaYoga. IMHO, any kind of concentrated effort at calming the mind =
down, in a controlled posture, is a part of Rajayoga. And pretty much every=
 seeker tries it to some extent. And it can work too depending on how much =
one is able to focus the mind. What we normally understand by the term medi=
tation is part of RajaYoga.


What Sri Ramakrishna *may* (it looks more rea=
sonable to me) have referred, and advised against,was possibly HathaYoga. N=
ow that is extremely dangerous=C2=A0 without the right environment, without=
 the right food, right habits, right control and most importantly the right=
 mentor/guide/guru.

Hatha Yoga forces the Kundalini to awaken using a guid=
ed combination of physical postures. This automatically presumes that the Y=
ogi must have a disease free body and a very stable mind. Mistakes here can=
 be extremely costly.


As such Swami Vivekananda was very adept in meditat=
ion practices. So that would technically fall under RajaYoga.

*=C2=A0=C2=
