t resist the urge to make a small comment on a line from the emails below.
=

<<These 4 yogas are listed in Bhagavat Gita, you can check it, I assure th=
ere are four of them.>>

Many great spiritual commentators, who are also fo=
unders of various sects within hinduism have commented and written purports=
 on the Gita. And each of these celebrated commentators have strongly disag=
reed with each other on various crucial points of interpretation of what th=
e text says. Some have read it to conclude that "X" yoga is better or highe=
r than "Y" yoga, or A philosophy is the right way to look at reality instea=
d of Y philosophy, or interpreted words/phrases in a sense that,sometimes d=
oes not make sense. And naturally followers of each of these great Gurus be=
lieve that their interpretation is the final and maximum one.

Reading all =
this can be confusing. Rather IMHO the Gita looks more like a book of progr=
essive arguments. Each section builds up into the next. It is not one again=
st the other, or one separate from the other. In that sense it is hardly a =
sectarian document, it does not say one specific interpretation of the spir=
itual reality is higher or better than another, but rather (probably becaus=
e the reality is so complex)accepts that multiple views points are *simulta=
neously* true.



Though
we have classified our understanding of the spirit=
ual path today 
into some broad exclusive basics like Jyana, Bhakti, Karma =
ETC ETC.. I am not sure if this is what the actual text intended to do.

Is=
 it not interesting that every chapter of the Gita is a Yoga? Arjuna's depr=
ession is also named as Yoga - Arjunavishad Yoga. [So many people get depre=
ssed about so many things daily, yet what exactly is special about Arjuna's=
 depression, or what is that depression which when it afflicts someone make=
s him/her=C2=A0 fit for receiving Divine knowledge?]

Therefore, IMO, one d=
oes not really go into Gyana Yoga by bypassing or staying away from Karma Y=
oga. As Karma Yoga gets perfected, automatically a higher Gyana comes into =
the seeker. And so on..

